lato}}, {{tt|it|pappa molle}}, {{tt|it|pappamolle}}, {{tt+|it|rammollito}}, {{tt+|it|fifone}}, {{tt+|it|codardo}}, {{tt+|it|cortigiano}}, {{tt+|it|mollusco}}, {{tt+|it|vigliacco}}, {{tt+|it|pusillanime}}, {{tt+|it|eunuco}}, {{tt+|it|debole|m}}, {{tt+|it|pisciasotto}}, {{tt+|it|cacasotto}}, {{tt+|it|pauroso}}, {{tt+|it|vile}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt|lt|bailus}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|РәСғРәР°РІРёСҶР°|f}}\n* Malay: {{tt|ms|pengecut}}\n* Norwegian: {{tt+|no|feiging|m}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|tchГіrz|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|covarde|m}}, {{tt+|pt|cobarde|m}}, {{tt+|pt|bundГЈo|m}}, {{tt+|pt|cagГЈo|m}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|СӮСҖСғСҒ|m}}, {{tt+|ru|СӮСҖСғСҒРёМҒС…Р°|f}} {{qualifier|female}}, {{tt+|ru|СӮСҖСғСҒРёСҲРәР°|m|f}} {{qualifier|mild}}, {{tt+|ru|СҒСҒСӢРәСғМҒРҪ|m}} {{qualifier|vulgar}}, {{tt+|ru|РұР·РҙСғРҪ|m}} {{qualifier|vulgar}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|РәСғРәР°РІРёСҶР°|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|kukavica|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|gallina|f}}, {{t+|es|cobarde|m}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|fegis|c}}, {{tt+|sv|mes|c}}\n* VolapГјk: {{qualifier|вҷӮвҷҖ}} {{tt+|vo|dredГ¶fan}}, {{qualifier|вҷӮ}} {{tt|vo|hidredГ¶fan}}, {{qualifier|вҷҖ}} {{tt|vo|jidredГ¶fan}}, {{qualifier|slang вҷӮвҷҖ}} {{tt|vo|dredajiedan}}, {{qualifier|slang вҷӮ}} {{tt|vo|dredahijiedan}}, {{qualifier|slang вҷҖ}} {{tt|vo|dredajijiedan}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt|zza|varing|f}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|young, attractive, slim man|twink}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|en|egg}}\n* {{l|en|poultry}}\n* [[рҹҗ”]]\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj}}\n\n# {{lb|en|informal|sometimes|derogatory}} [[cowardly|Cowardly]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:cowardly|Thesaurus:afraid}}\n#: {{ux|en|Why do you refuse to fight? Huh, I guess you're just too '''chicken'''.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|chicken out}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nShortening of {{m|en|chicken out}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[avoid]] a [[situation]] one is [[afraid]] of.\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Max Shulman|title=Anyone Got a Match?|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Harper (publisher)|Harper & Row]]|year=1964|page=31|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=uhL4AHsb8VEC&q=%22chickened%22+-%22chickened+out%22&dq=%22chickened%22+-%22chickened+out%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBzgKahUKEwj_-5fn3pjJAhWIaT4KHfo_CSs|oclc=176716|passage=For the umpteenth time, I '''chickened'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Aidan Chambers|title=The Chicken Run: A Play for Young People|location=Oxford|publisher=[[w:Heinemann (publisher)|Heinemann Educational Publishers]]|year=1968|section=act II, scene v|page=81|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=EDpYANpo4CAC&pg=PA82|isbn=978-0-435-23167-5|passage=ABE: What ''are'' you chucking it for, then? You're running, aren't you? Running, cos you '''chickened'''. <br> SLIM: All right, so I '''chickened'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Anne M. Brown|chapter=James Day|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=0f4QBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT25|title=Belonging: The Story of How James Became a Brown|location=Acacia Ridge, Qld.|publisher=Australian eBook Publisher|year=2014|isbn=978-1-925177-25-1|passage=To reach the lower branches of the blackwood one had to swing Tarzan-like across a narrow gully choked with gorse and blackberries. {{...}} [T]he challenge of the rope swing was definitely more in James' line. {{...}} Even if he slipped and failed, or worse, '''chickened''', they would be unlikely to judge too harshly.}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{ety|en|:af|chick|-en<pos:plural ending><id:plural noun>|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|en|noun form}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|_|dialectal|_|or|_|obsolete}} {{plural of|en|chick}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1669|title=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London|passage=The 21 or 22 day the '''Chicken''' are hatch'd; {{...}}}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia}}\n* {{pedia|chicken (food)}}\n* {{pedia|chicken (game)}}\n* {{pedia|chicken (gay slang)}}\n* {{pedia|chicken (disambiguation)}}\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ccehikn|check in|check-in|checkin'|in check}}\n\n{{cln|en|adjectives ending in -en}}\n{{C|en|Chickens|Dances|Meats|Poultry}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|sco|en|chicken}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{sco-noun}}\n\n# {{l|en|chicken}}"}}